Analysis plan

Regarding the provided hypothesis it is assumed that there is a negative linear relationship between studentsâ performance on the statistics module and both general anxiety and statistics anxiety. Hence, due to this linearity, a generalized linear model will be an appropriate fit for testing this hypothesis. Also, since two predictors are introduced (general anxiety and statistics anxiety), a generalized linear model with multiple predictors will be applied to this analysis. So, to test the following hypothesis:

  • \(H_1\): studentsâ performance on their statistics module (stats_exam) will be predicted by their level of both statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety) and general anxiety (gen_anxiety). Both types of anxiety should have a negative relationship with performance on the statistics assignment.

The following model will be fitted:

\[ \hat{performance_i} = \hat{b_0} + \hat{b_1}general \ anxiety_i \ + \hat{b_2}statistics \ anxiety_i \ + \varepsilon_i \]

Data will be summarized and visualized as follows:

  • Descriptive statistics (mean, standard deviation, inter-quartile range, skewness, kurtosis, and confidence intervals) of statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety), general anxiety (gen_anxiety), and performance on statistical module (stats_exam) will be provided to explore distributional properties and central tendencies related to data.

  • Histograms of general anxiety (gen_anxiety), statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety), and studentsâ performance on the statistics module (stats_exam) to explore their distribution pattern and outliers.

  • Box plots for general anxiety (gen_anxiety), statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety), and studentsâ performance on the statistics module (stats_exam) to explore possible outlier data.

  • Table of outlier data using standardized residuals using the criteria of: \(z \geq 2.58 \ or \ z \leq -2.58\) to define outlier data with a \(99\%\) confidence level.

  • Scatter plots of general anxiety (gen_anxiety) against srudentsâ performance in the statistics module (stats_exam) and statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety) against srudentsâ performance in the statistics module (stats_exam) to verify the linearity assumption for a generalized linear model.

  • Scatter plot of leverage (x-axis) against standardized residuals (y-axis) will be utilized to highlight influential cases.

The generalized linear model will be fit. To check the generalizability of our results and to ensure that the utilized model is proper, assumptions of a generalized linear model should be checked as follows:

  • Linearity: Since we are fitting a generalized linear model, it is the most important assumption. The relationship between predictor variables (general anxiety (gen_anxiety) and statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety)) and outcome variables (studentsâ performance on the statistics exam (stats_exam)) should be linear. This assumption will be evaluated using Scatter plots of general anxiety (gen_anxiety) against srudentsâ performance on the statistics module (stats_exam) and statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety) against srudentsâ performance on the statistics module (stats_exam). Additionally, a scatter plot of fitted values (x-axis) against the residual values (y-axis) would be used as further evidence for linearity.

  • Homoscedasticity: The variance of residuals should be consistent at different levels of the predictor variable. To check this assumption a scatter plot of fitted values (x-axis) against residuals (y-axis) will be utilized.

  • Independence: The residual of one case should not be predicted based on the residual of another case. To check this assumption, a scatter plot of case number (x-axis) against standardized residual values (y-axis) would be used. Residuals should be randomly scattered over the length of the x-axis.

  • Normality: Normality of model errors (residuals) should be assessed. Since the sample size is large enough, the normality of sampling distribution due to the central limit theorem (CLT) is assumed without further checking. To check the normality, a q-q plot of standardized residuals will be utilized.

Contingency plans if any of the assumptions are not met:

  • Linearity: If this assumption is violated, the generalized linear model would not fit anymore and there is a need to utilize non-linear models.

  • Homoscedasticity: If this assumption is violated, while estimates of betas would not impacted, standard error will become incorrect which makes p-value, t-value, and confidence intervals incorrect. In the scenario, robust models or bootstrapping should be utilized.

  • Independence: If this assumption is violated, a multilevel model should be utilized.

  • Normality: If this assumption is violated, robust models or bootstrapping should be utilized.

If the assumptions are met, then the fitted generalized linear model is appropriate and results are interpretable and generalizable. For interpretations, \(\alpha > 0.05\) will be used as a significance criterion. However, if the assumptions are not met, a robust model of the generalized linear model will be used. Again, for this model, \(\alpha > 0.05\) will be used as a significance criterion. Also, to ensure the validity of the p-value, confidence intervals will be checked to ensure that they are not crossing zero in both scenarios (with and without meeting assumptions).

Summary statistics and data visualization

Overall, the skewness and kurtosis for these three variables are small and near 0 which means they are close to the normal distribution. Also, no missing value exists in the data.

hist_stats_anxiety + hist_general_anxiety + hist_stats_exam

The provided FigureÂ 1 illustrates histograms of statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety), general anxiety (gen_anxiety), and studentsâ performance on statistics exam (stats_exam). While general anxiety and statistics anxiety are near a normal distribution, studentsâ performance demonstrates a bimodal histogram.

box_stats_anxiety + box_general_anxiety + box_stats_exam

Illustrated box plots in FigureÂ 2 show inter-quartile range for statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety), general anxiety (gen_anxiety), and studentsâ performance on statistics exam (stats_exam). The mean for general anxiety and statistics anxiety are close to each other (around 40) while the mean for studentsâ performance is near 50. Outliers are shown in these box plots with dots. As is presented the numbers of outlier cases compared to the large sample size (n = 1576) are pretty few. Consequently, it is reasonable to fit a model without much concern related to outlier cases. Also, the results general anxiety and statistics anxiety are both in the range of 0-65 which means no obvious error in data entry can be seen for these two variables.

The TableÂ 2 shows that only 11 cases introduced as outlier cases in accordance to their performance in the statistics exam. Again, compared to the large sample of 1576 students, 11 outliers are not going to have significant impact on model fitting. To find this outliers, \(99\%\) confidence level was assumed with \(z \geq 2.58 \ or \ z \leq -2.58\).

scat_stats_exam + scat_general_exam

Regarding the hypothesis, a generalized linear model will be fitted. However, linearity is the major assumption of general linear model. Hence, the relationship between predictors (statistical anxiety and general anxiety) and outcome (studentsâ performance) should be linear. According to FigureÂ 3 both of general anxiety and statistical anxiety are showing a linear relationship with studentsâ performance. However, in contrast to researchersâ hypothesis, they are not showing a same pattern in their relationships. While the relationship between general anxiety and studentsâ performance is positive, the relationship between statistics anxiety and studentsâ performance is negative. Overall, these scatter plots are showing linearity which make fitting general linear model reasonable.

Model Assumptions

Influential_cases

The threshold for leverage is calculated as: \(\frac{3(p+1)}{n}\) where p is the number of predictor variables. Hence, in our case the threshold would be \(0.0057\) . Since the sample size is large, and number of cases with leverage value greater than 0.0057 is limited, it is assumed that these cases would not influence the model.

normality_model

One of the assumptions for generalized linear model is the normality of errors (residuals) and normality of sampling distribution. Regarding normality for sampling distribution, since the sample size is large enough (n = 1567), in accordance to central limit theorem (CLT), sampling distribution is normally distributed. FigureÂ 5 is a q-q plot for analyzing the normality of errors (residuals). Since the line is following the diagonal line, it is reasonable to mention that the residuals are normally distributed. So, the assumption of normality has been met.

independece_scatter

Independence of errors (residuals) is another assumption generalized linear model. Residual of one case should not be predicted by another caseâs residual. Hence, by plotting residuals in the length of case ids (x-axis) no pattern should be seen and residuals should be scattered randomly. As is seen in FigureÂ 6 , residuals are randomly scattered along the x-axis without following a specific pattern. Hence, the assumption of independence residuals is met.

linearity_homoscedasticity

Final two assumptions of generalized linear model are linearity and homoscedasticity. Previously, the linearity of the relationships between predictor variables and outcome variable was evaluated FigureÂ 3 . However, in FigureÂ 7 a further evidence for linearity of the model is presented. Since the line is not curved shape, the assumption of linearity was met for this model.

Homoscedasticity means that the variance of residuals should be consistent at different values of predictor variable. To meet homoscedasticity assumption,dots in the FigureÂ 7 which shows residuals (y-axis) in the legnth of fitted values (x-axis) should be like a rectangle to show a consistency. However, in the FigureÂ 7 a funnel shape can be seen. Seeing this funnel shape pattern means that the assumption of homoscedasticity was not met. Not meeting this assumptions would leave estimate of betas unbiased. However, by not giving a correct standard error, can influence all other parameters namely, t-value, p-value, and confidence intervals. Therefore, normal model of generalized linear model would not be appropriate for this model. So, for testing the hypothesis, a robust model of generalized linear model will be utilized. Robust models are less sensitive to these assumptions and outliers, therefore they would be an appropriate option.

Statistical model

robust_model_stats

According to the results of TableÂ 3 there is a significant positive relationship between general anxiety (gen_anxiety) and studentsâ performance (stats_exam), \(t=3.99,p<0.05\). Also, there is a significant negative relationship between statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety) and studentsâ performance (stats_exam), \(t=-8.32,p<0.05\). However, since the sample size is significantly large, p-value cannot be a proper measure to define the significancy of the results because large samples would increase the possibility of demonstrating significant p-value without meaningful effects. For valid interpretation, beta estimates (coefficients) should be interpreted. Beta estimates for the relationship between general anxiety (gen_anxiety) and studentsâ performance (stats_exam) is \(\hat{B} = 0.23\) which means as the general anxiety increases by one unit, the studentsâ performance expected to increase by 0.22 of a unit. Even though \(\hat{B}=0.23\) is a low effect, but in the context of this research, this result is meaningful. According to FigureÂ 2 the mean of studentsâ performance is around 50, and the IQR is around 37.5 to 62.5, hence if general anxiety increases by 10 units, studentsâ performance increases by 2.2 points which seems meaningful. Additionally, the confidence intervals for this beta estimate are 0.12 and 0.34 which do not cross zero. This gives us another clue to accept the significance of the p-value in reality. Beta estimates for the relationship between statistics anxiety (stats_anxiety) and studentsâ performance (stats_exam) is \(\hat{B}=-0.46\) which means as the statistics anxiety increases by one unit, the studentsâ performance expected to decrease by 0.46 of a unit. This beta estimate illustrates a moderate effect. If statistics anxiety increases by 10 units, studentsâ performance decreases by 4.6 points which seems significantly meaningful. Additionally, the confidence intervals for this beta estimate are -0.56 and -0.35 which do not cross zero. This gives us another clue to accept the significance of the p-value in reality.

Summary

To sum up, the model did not support the hypothesis, that both types of anxiety should have a negative relationship with performance on the statistics exam. According to TableÂ 3, while statistics anxiety showed a significant moderate negative relationship with studentsâ performance, general anxiety showed a significant low positive relationship with studentsâ performance. Hence, the null hypothesis (\(H_0\)) was approved and researchersâ hypothesis (\(H_1\)) was rejected.

Overall, due to the linear pattern of the hypothesis, generalized linear model with multiple predictors was decided to explain the relationship. While the assumptions of normality FigureÂ 5 , linearity FigureÂ 7 FigureÂ 3, and independence FigureÂ 6 was met, the assumption of homoscedasticity @fit-hetro did not meet. Hence, instead of a normal generalized linear model a robust model of generalized linear model was fitted which was less sensitive to assumptions and outliers. Even though the hypothesis was rejected, the model was a good fit for this scenario.
